subQuestions.solutionSteps:
1. In the first round, divide 100 people into groups of 10, resulting in 10 groups, and 10 tests are needed for pooled testing;
2. The two infected patients are in the same group, the pooled test result of this group is positive, and 10 individual tests are needed for the 10 people in the group;
3. The total number of tests is the sum of the two rounds, which is 10+10=20.

1. Analyze the possible values of X: 20 tests when the two patients are in the same group, and 10+10+10=30 tests when they are in different groups (needing individual tests for two positive groups), so X takes 20 and 30;
2. Determine the probabilities: $P(X=20)=\frac{1}{11}$, $P(X=30)=1-\frac{1}{11}=\frac{10}{11}$;
3. List the probability distribution: $P(X=20)=\frac{1}{11}$, $P(X=30)=\frac{10}{11}$;
4. Calculate the mathematical expectation: Substitute into the expectation formula $E(X)=x_1P_1+x_2P_2$, we get $E(X)=20×\frac{1}{11}+30×\frac{10}{11}=\frac{320}{11}$.
